midazole, imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, AICN); convergence and network connectivity are robust (no isolated subgraphs, >3 degrees for all hubs). Known bottlenecks (formamidine and erythrose scarcity; fragility of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) are correctly reflected per research findings. Alternate routes to imidazole (Debus-Radziszewski, Sutherland cascade, HCN photochemistry) are included but explicitly shown as dead ends regarding histidine, which is both chemically accurate and aligns with all cited literature. Literature integration is exemplary: every reaction is annotated and referenced in accordance with experimental precedent, and the network addresses all key challenges noted in the research (prebiotic plausibility, environmental transitions, stability, yields). To further strengthen the model, specific mineral catalyst annotations at each step would add further realism, and current knowledge gaps (e.g., imidazole-to-histidine plausible transitions) are transparently acknowledged. This is an excellent synthesis network, state-of-the-art for astrochemical and prebiotic modeling.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 1.0,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 1.0\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_006": 1.0, "rxn_002": 0.8, "rxn_003": 0.85, "rxn_004": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.85, "pathway_coherence": 0.95, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 1.0, "overall_confidence": 0.9, "feedback": "This pathway accurately reproduces the only experimentally demonstrated prebiotic synthesis of histidine (Shen et al., 1987/1990). Each reaction is supported by the literature. The weak points are the prebiotic plausibility of formamidine formation (labile, low environmental concentrations) and the low yield of the key Amadori rearrangement, but these limitations are authentic and well-reasoned per research consensus. Environmental transitions are realistic, using surface/wet\u2013dry/aqueous for rele